Assisted death bill heads to Jerry Brown

By David Siders, dsiders@sacbee.com

Dan Diaz, whose wife brought national attention to the physician-assisted death movement before dying last year, stood at the back of Senate chambers Friday – the bill he championed about to pass but its ultimate prospects still unclear.

"(Jerry) Brown's the big question," said Diaz, the widower of Brittany Maynard. "He hasn't given us an indication one way or another." (Diaz is pictured with his wife, Brittany Maynard, from TheBrittanyFund.org 2014 file photo)

Following a 23-14 vote in the Senate, Brown will now decide whether to sign or veto legislation to let doctors prescribe life-ending drugs to people with terminal illnesses.

Brown, a former Jesuit seminarian has declined to state a position on the measure. His office released a statement last month criticizing the use of a special legislative session to advance the bill outside of the normal legislative process.

The Democratic governor rarely comments on pending litigation, but Diaz noted that the criticism came from a spokeswoman – not Brown himself – and he said he "would like to think it was simply a comment about the procedural stuff."

The Senate passed the bill on the final day of the legislative session, after the lower house moved it earlier this week.

Advocates called the measure an act of compassion for people afflicted by terminal illnesses. The bill included language limiting assisted death to patients predicted to die within six months and requiring approval from multiple physicians.

In an emotional debate lasting more than an hour, Sen. Lois Wolk, D-Davis, said the bill would help "eliminate the needless pain and the long suffering of those who are dying," while Sen. Bill Monning, D-Carmel, called choices at the end of life a fundamental right.

Sen. Mark Leno, D-San Francisco, said that of the hundreds of bills that run through the Legislature each year, there are few that "impact us so profoundly as a bill like this."

The bill passed the Democratic-controlled Senate over the objections of many Republicans.

Sen. Bob Huff, R-San Dimas, called the bill "assisted killing." He and other opponents of the bill said they feared the availability of physician-assisted death would exert pressure on frail and elderly people to end their lives to avoid burdening others.

Sen. Jeff Stone, R-Temecula, said diagnoses of terminal illness are sometimes wrong, and Sen. Ted Gaines, R-Roseville, said his vote against the bill was "a stand for the dignity of life."

The legislation was modeled on a law enacted in Oregon in 1997. Washington and Vermont have since legalized assisted death.

In a major lift for the California legislation, the California Medical Association adopted a neutral position after years of opposition. But the Catholic Church and organizations representing oncologists and the disabled lobbied against the bill.

Despite a national campaign centered around Maynard, proponents of the assisted death bill failed earlier this year to move the legislation out of the Assembly Health Committee. By re-introducing the measure in a special session, they circumvented that committee.

Last year, Brown called Maynard, a Bay Area woman with brain cancer, days before she died. Maynard had traveled to Oregon to take advantage of that state's law.

Diaz has declined to discuss specifics of their conversation, but he said Maynard pressed the governor on the issue.

Diaz said he could understand Brown's concerns about legislative procedure, but he said terminally ill people – some of whom attended the hearing Friday – "don't have the time for some legislative calendar to just match up perfectly."

#TBT: Sacramento's love of bicycle racing goes back to the 1880s when local clubs were formed to compete in long-distance rides. On April 24, 1892, the Capital City Wheelmen bested the Oak Leaf Club of Stockton in a 52-mile relay race between the two towns. That Sunday at 1:30 the Oak Leafs left Stockton for Sacramento and the Wheelmen left Sacramento for Stockton. The latter completed the trip in three hours, nine minutes, beating Stockton by 11 minutes. The Oak Leafs later protested that Sacramento enjoyed a tailwind part of the way.

#TBT: The March 9, 1934 edition of The Bee included the first appearance of "Katherine Kitchen." Miss Kitchen was the pen name of a succession of home economists and food writers that dispensed culinary advice for decades in the paper. The first columns were written by Peg Brawley of the company's Promotions Department. Featured recipe that day was "St. Patrick's Salad," a green concoction consisting of lime gelatin, canned pineapple, chopped nuts and sweet pickle, topped with mayonnaise. Happy St. Patrick's Day 2015!

NEW: SACBEE HIGH SCHOOL SPORTS SHOW -- The Sacramento Bee and Mike Finnerty have agreed to partner on a cable TV high school sports show. "The Sacramento Bee High School Sports Show" will be co-hosted by Finnerty and longtime Bee sports writer Joe Davidson. The 30-minute show will air on Comcast SportsNet California throughout the week with game highlights, coach and player interviews and big-picture discussion on high school sports.

Finnerty currently co-hosts and produces "All-City Preps" on Comcast SportsNet. That show will change its name in August to The Bee show, and each show after airing on Comcast will later be shown on sacbee.com.

Congratulations to Phillip Reese and Cynthia Hubert who today were awarded the prestigious George Polk Award for their investigative reporting on Nevada Patient Busing. Their series found that a psychiatric hospital in Nevada had bused hundreds of mentally ill patients to cities around the country, often to places where they had no connections or treatment arrangements. Yesterday, Reese and Hubert were awarded the Worth Bingham Prize from Harvard University's Nieman Foundation. See their work at www.sacbee.com/nevadapatientbusing

Today The Bee newsroom celebrated the McClatchy President's Award to reporter Marjie Lundstrom and photographer Manny Crisostomo. 

Earlier this month, the McClatchy Company announced the winners of 10 President's Awards for journalism excellence in 2011 for superior work in investigative reporting, breaking news coverage, narrative writing and digital journalism. The company also recognized two newspapers with special prizes for innovation and entrepreneurship.

About Marjie and Manny the judges wrote:

The Sacramento Bee
Girl with 100 Scars

Marjie Lundstrom's series on Lilly Manning begins as a horror story of unspeakable dimensions, but ends up as a tale of triumph and recovery. Along the way, the stories uncover shortcomings of social services that visited the girl's home 11 separate times without discovering the abuse taking place under the roof of this troubled home. The work is a tribute to the remarkable young girl at the center of this story and also to the power of storytelling in the hands of true veterans.

See the "Girl with 100 scars" project at www.sacbee.com/manning

Kings make their NBA draft pick today. On Friday at noon, Sports Editor Bill Bradley will host a live chat to discuss the pick.
Marcos Breton will appear on Jim Rome is Burning on ESPN at 1:30 pm (PT) today.

Bee Senior Photographer Renee C. Byer wins the 2007 Pulitzer Prize for feature photography for her work on "A Mother's Journey," which told the story of a single mother, Cyndie French, and her son Derek, who was dying of cancer.
Sacramento Bee Publisher Janis Heaphy speaks with employees who had gathered in the newsroom to celebrate The Bee's 150th anniversary.
Associate editor Tom Philp wins the Pulitzer Prize for editorial writing, for a series about draining and restoring the Hetch Hetchy Valley.
Saddam Hussein captured
Arnold becomes governor of California

Kobe Bryant and Scot Pollard in the 2002 NBA Western Conference Finals. The Sacramento Kings lose the seventh game to the Los Angeles Lakers, the furthest the Kings have gone in the playoffs since moving to the city.
Dinger, the mascot, leads the crowd in cheering the entrance of the team at the debut River Cats game at Raley Field, May 15, 2000.

A former college professor named Ted Kaczynski pleads guilty to carrying out 16 bombings over a 20-year period. The "Unabomber" killed three people, including two in Sacramento, and injured 23. He is sentenced to life imprisonment.

A swarm of storms hits Sacramento, killing at least nine, flooding 250 square miles in the Central Valley and destroying or damaging more than 25,000 residences and businesses. The floods trigger the evacuation of 120,000 people, the state's largest emergency exodus. Here a large home is surrounded by water in Wilton after storms drove the Cosumnes River over its levees.

On a day that could be considered the paper's greatest, The Bee wins two Pulitzer Prizes. One, in the beat reporting category, is for a series of stories by science writer Deborah Blum on medical research using primates. The other, for public service, is for a series led by Tom Knudson on the environmental deterioration of the Sierra.
Six people are killed after four gunmen take 41 hostages at the Good Guys store on Stockton Boulevard and police storm the store after an hours-long standoff.

Human remains are found in the backyard of an F Street boardinghouse. Police question the manager, then let her walk away. Dorothea Montalvo Puente is arrested five days later in Los Angeles. She is convicted on five murder counts and sentenced to life in prison.
Regional Transit's long-awaited light rail prepared to roll away from a stop at the K Street Mall as a collection of blue and yellow balloons floated into the air at the system's 1987 debut.

Strawberry Manor subdivision view from the northeast in Del Paso Heights lies awash  in floodwaters from Arcade Creek. Ten days of fierce storms cause widespread flooding and the region teeters on the edge of major disaster. The scare prompts requirements for flood insurance for thousands and discussion of whether the area is adequately prepared.
The Sacramento Kings, an NBA refugee from Kansas City, play their first game at a converted warehouse.

A wayward California gray whale, dubbed Humphrey, swims up the Sacramento River and hangs around for about three weeks before being safely coaxed back out to sea. Here volunteers in a chase boat try to herd him down the San Joaquin River in Antioch, Calif.

UC Davis campus police arrested anti-apartheid protesters April 24, 1985 after they refused to leave the administration building. Protests against apartheid were also held at eight other UC campuses, Stanford University and at least 100 colleges across the nation. In Berkeley, nearly 7,000 people, including 13 regents, streamed into the university gymnasium to hear arguments against continuing UC investment in companies doing business in South Africa. The following year, the Regents agreed to a three-year plan to divest over $1 billion in holdings from South Africa (Sacramento Bee / Dick Schmidt)
Anne Rudin becomes Sacramento's first directly elected female mayor.
Queen Elizabeth II visits Sacramento and has lunch at the Capitol with Gov. George Deukmejian. The Nut Tree restaurant of Vacaville caters.

Capitol building restoration circa 1981. The state Capitol reopened in 1982 after a $68 million renovation project designed to make the building safer in earthquakes and restore it to its former glory.
The Three Mile Island incident sparked protests at Rancho Seco in 1979. A public referendum vote closed the plant in 1989.

Richard Trenton Chase was arrested for murders dubbed "the vampire killings," because he claimed to have drunk the blood of victims. He was sentenced to life and killed himself in prison with a drug overdose.

Chibi, has second thoughts about wandering around Land Park in the snow. Land Park pro Don Oreb braved the weather to give a putting lesson to 4-year-old Rickey Gregson on February 5, 1976. (Leo Neibaur/The Sacramento Bee)
Inge Gough, Maggie Gomez and Sherry McAtee enjoy a battle during the snow on February 5, 1976. (Erhardt Krause/The Sacramento Bee)
Marlyn Crowe decorates her creation on February 5, 1976 in Sacramento. (Ehrhardt Krause/The Sacramento Bee)

Sonny Valine wonders if it would be worth it to play a round at Land Park on February 5, 1976. He decided against it because his golf balls were the same color as the fairways. (Leo Neibaur/The Sacramento Bee)
Stan Livermon and Charles Brown put the finishing touches on their snowman, February 5, 1976. (Erhardt Krause/The Sacramento Bee)
Snowflakes in downtown Sacramento. Sacramento received two inches of snow on February 5, 1976. (Harlin Smith/The Sacramento Bee)

Lynette "Squeaky" Fromme, a member of the Charles Manson Family cult, points a gun at President Ford as he walks through Capitol Park. Fromme is knocked to the ground by a Secret Service agent and later sentenced to life in prison.

Members of a would-be revolutionary group called the Symbionese Liberation Army rob a Carmichael bank, killing a 42-year-old homemaker who is depositing her church's collection money. In February 2003, four former members of the group are finally sentenced to prison for their roles in the robbery, followed by a fifth in 2004.
LBJ signs the landmark 1964 Civil Rights Act (Sacramento Bee, July 3, 1964).
History on the front pages of The Sacramento Bee
What started as a friendly game between local peace officers and firefighters in 1974 grew into a huge annual event attracting some 32,000 fans. This fisheye photo was taken at the 1978 Pig Bowl.
The once-opulent Alhambra Theatre is torn down to make room for a Safeway grocery store.

The front page from the Sacramento Bee newspaper from September 25, 1972.  The page shows the explosion and crash of a F86 Saber jet that lost control and landed into Farrell's Ice Cream Parlour on Freeport Boulevard, killing 22 people in the process.
A Korean War-era jet performing in an air show at Executive Airport on Freeport Boulevard crashes into a nearby Farrell's ice cream store. The crash kills 22, many of them kids attending a party.
Mark Spitz of the Arden Hills Swim Club wins the first of seven gold medals at the Olympic Games in Munich.
A farm labor contractor named Juan Corona is arrested for the murders of 25 farm workers near Yuba City. He is convicted in 1973 and sentenced to 25 life sentences. (Corona pictured here in 1987.)
The nearly completed Interstate 5 Freeway in 1970. The freeway had the unfortunate effect of cutting off the historic area from downtown.
The nearly completed Interstate 5 Freeway in 1970. The freeway had the unfortunate effect of cutting off the historic area from downtown.
Children play in Sacramento's K Street Mall a few days before its formal dedication in 1969.
Children play in Sacramento's K Street Mall a few days before its formal dedication in 1969.
#TBT: Dr. Martin Luther King visited Sacramento on Oct. 16, 1967 and spoke to a crowd of 7,000 at (then) Sacramento State College.  (Sacramento Bee photo by Erhardt Krause)

Two dozen armed members of the militant Black Panthers group march into the Capitol to protest a gun-control bill. A dozen get as far as the Assembly chamber before State Police disarm them. It's later determined the protesters broke no weapons laws because the guns were not concealed.

Two dozen armed members of the militant Black Panthers group march into the Capitol to protest a gun-control bill. A dozen get as far as the Assembly chamber before State Police disarm them. It's later determined the protesters broke no weapons laws because the guns were not concealed.

Construction of Folsom Dam began in 1948, and had progressed enough by December 1955 to help prevent the American River from flooding during torrential rains. The $102 million dam was officially dedicated May 5, 1956, with a crowd of 25,000 treated to water-skiing demonstrations and boat races on Folsom Lake as well as an air show.
Torrential rains trigger massive flooding in the Central Valley. Yuba City is inundated and Marysville is turned into an island. By the time the storms are over, 74 Northern Californians are dead.
Torrential rains trigger massive flooding in the Central Valley. Yuba City is inundated and Marysville is turned into an island. By the time the storms are over, 74 Northern Californians are dead.
The Bee moves to its new $2.3 million plant at 21st and Q Streets.

The City of San Francisco streamliner with 226 passengers and crew aboard is snowbound near Emigrant Gap in Placer County in mid-January 1952 as the Sierra Nevada is buried in one of the worst blizzards in history. It was three harrowing days before all aboard were rescued. No one killed or seriously injured.

It was three harrowing days before all aboard were rescued. No one killed or seriously injured.

Overflow crowd 1948 opening day Edmonds Field, home of the Sacramento Solons. Later that year a fire burns down the sports venue. Edmonds (on the current site of the Target store on Broadway) is rebuilt in time for the 1949 season.
Streetcars photographed in 1940 at 8th and K streets. Sacramento's last two streetcar lines make their final runs in 1947.
Streetcars photographed in 1940 at 8th and K streets. Sacramento's last two streetcar lines make their final runs in 1947.
Scoopy (seen here with cousin Gaby) the cartoon bee designed by Walt Disney, makes his debut as The Bee's official icon.

Mary Lou McDonald, Marjorie Hack, Willie Hagan and Bernice Gaunt, left to right, could not resist the temptation Saturday to enjoy some snowball hurling as cars skidded along K Street. The March 14, 1942 storm dropped 2 inches of snow on Sacramento.
Snow lines the cityscape in downtown Sacramento near the Capitol. The March 14, 1942 storm dropped 2 inches of snow on Sacramento.

The weight of the water-soaked, icy sleet proved to be too much for a section of the warehouse roof at the Bert McDowell Wholesale Grocery at Front and J Streets. The March 14, 1942 storm dropped 2 inches of snow on Sacramento
Skiing was only one of the sports enjoyed on the Capitol grounds. Henri Lappi is shown on the skis with deserted driveway beyond. The March 14, 1942 storm dropped 2 inches of snow on Sacramento.

Snowmen appeared everywhere. This one, at 10th and S Streets, was constructed by Muriel Nunn, Mrs. Lou Bordisso, and Dolores Nunn, left to right. The March 14, 1942 storm dropped 2 inches of snow on Sacramento.
A solder stands guard at the Tower Bridge in 1942. Following the bombing at Pearl Harbor, the military coordinated security at facilities vulnerable to possible attack.

In 1938 the Sacramento Air Depot begins repairing planes, engines and flight instruments. In 1939, it's renamed McClellan, after Army Air Corps Maj. Hezekiah McClellan, who was killed in World War I. Here, Gen. George Marshall is guest speaker at the dedication ceremonies.

The Tower Bridge was opened with great fanfare in 1935. It was built at an original cost of $994,000 and replaced the old M Street Bridge. Considered to be the "gateway to Sacramento," it was appropriate to the growing status of Sacramento as the capital of California.

The Tower Bridge was opened with great fanfare in 1935. It was built at an original cost of $994,000 and replaced the old M Street Bridge. Considered to be the "gateway to Sacramento," it was appropriate to the growing status of Sacramento as the capital of California.

Dec. 11, 1932 was the coldest temperature ever recorded in Sacramento. The record low was part of a frigid period that lasted from Dec. 9-15. Crops suffered, park ponds froze, radiators ruptured, water stopped flowing through pipes, a sheepherder froze to death and frozen goldfish miraculously came back to life after being thawed. Read more: http://a.sacb.ee/C3F03aX
A formation of Martin MB-2 bombers flies over what was then Mather Field in Sacramento County in 1930 during maneuvers that involved Air Corps aircraft from across the country.
A formation of Martin MB-2 bombers flies over what was then Mather Field in Sacramento County in 1930 during maneuvers that involved Air Corps aircraft from across the country.
Sacramento Municipal Airport, shown in this 1932 photograph, south of downtown Sacramento. The airport was dedicated two years earlier. It is now Executive Airport on Freeport Boulevard.
In 1927, the City of Sacramento completed the Memorial Auditorium.

Shown in this 1931 aerial view, Sacramento Junior College, today's Sacramento City College, established its campus on Freeport Blvd. near Sutterville Road in 1926. This view, looking east, also shows the Western Pacific Railroad shops and the Curtis Park subdivision just beyond Hughes Stadium.

During the decade following World War I, Sacramento developed an identifiable skyline. The California State Life building at the far left (10th and J streets), was build in 1924, and reached 216 feet. Two years later, the Elks Temple in the middle of the picture (11th and J streets), rose to 226 feet.

No part of the state was painted prettier than Capitol Park when a mantle of snow fell last night. The wide lawns were blanketed and the limbs of the evergreen trees were bowed down with a white load. Sacramento received 1.5 inches of snow on January 30, 1922. From microfilm of The Sacramento Bee, January 30, 1922.

Sacramento children wear masks, ordered by the city, during the worldwide flu epidemic of 1918-19, which killed more than 25 million. About 4,500 cases were reported in the city, with about 500 deaths.

The two-lane Yolo Causeway is opened. The $400,000 structure drastically cuts the commute between Sacramento and San Francisco during the rainy season. Motorists still have to take ferries at the Carquinez Strait and Oakland.
Aug. 1, 1914: Germany declares war on Russia (Sacramento Bee, Aug. 3, 1914).
Sixth (or seventh) grade class picture taken in the Harkness Grammar School a 10th and P Streets in Sacramento, about 1913. Courtesy Mrs. Anna Butler.
